data.content:
Windows
Windows is an operating system by Microsoft that will be installed alongside Ubuntu on the dual-boot system.<SEP>Windows is an operating system used by many users and can be part of a dual-boot configuration with Ubuntu.

Ubuntu
Ubuntu is a free, open-source operating system developed by Canonical that can be installed with Windows in a dual-boot configuration.<SEP>Ubuntu is an operating system that can be installed alongside Windows in a dual boot setup.

BIOS/UEFI
BIOS and UEFI are firmware interfaces for computers; BIOS is traditional while UEFI is modern. Understanding their settings is crucial for setting up a dual boot system.

Secure Boot
A security standard that prevents unauthorized operating systems from loading during the startup process, which may need to be disabled when installing Ubuntu.

GRUB bootloader
The GRUB bootloader is a program that allows users to choose between multiple installed operating systems at boot time.

Rufus
Rufus is a free, open-source software used for creating bootable USB drives, utilized in preparing to install Ubuntu.

External hard drive/cloud storage
Refers to mediums recommended for backing up important data before initiating changes to the system during dual-boot setup.

File Explorer
A file management application included with Windows, used to check disk space and manage files in preparation for partitioning for Ubuntu installation.

Windows Disk Management
A utility in Windows that allows users to view and manage the disk drives installed on their computer. It is used to shrink partitions and make space for installing Ubuntu.

partition
A division of a hard drive into separate, manageable sections. Partitions are crucial when setting up a dual-boot system to allocate specific areas for each operating system.

GRUB
GRUB (Grand Unified Bootloader) is a bootloader program that allows the user to select which operating system to boot, particularly in dual-boot setups like Ubuntu and Windows.

BIOS
BIOS (Basic Input/Output System) is firmware used during the initial startup of a computer to set hardware parameters and select the default boot device.

Boot-Repair
Boot-Repair is a tool that can be used from a live Ubuntu session to fix boot issues, particularly those involving GRUB not detecting installed operating systems.

Wi-Fi
Wi-Fi is a technology used for wireless local area networking, important to check during system installation or troubleshooting.

display resolution
Display resolution refers to the clarity of text and images on a screen, which should be checked post-installation to ensure settings are correct.

software settings
Software settings include configurations for various programs and operating systems that may need adjustment after installation or troubleshooting.
